# Always deploy after changes

Whenever you finish making code or content changes in this project:

1. Commit the relevant changes (user has requested ongoing deploy-after-change).
2. Push to `origin` on the current branch (usually `main`) so Vercel production redeploys.
3. Wait until the newest deployment is **Ready**.
4. **Mandatory verification** — fetch the real production URL and confirm the new HTML is live:
   - Primary URL: https://chunyang-lou-geospatial-software-engineer.vercel.app
   - Also keep https://bluesky613-gis.vercel.app in sync when aliasing.
   - Check for expected markers (e.g. a unique class/string from the change) AND absence of removed content.
5. If the primary domain still serves an old build while a newer deployment is Ready, immediately re-point the aliases:
   ```bash
   npx vercel alias set <latest-deployment-url> chunyang-lou-geospatial-software-engineer.vercel.app
   npx vercel alias set <latest-deployment-url> bluesky613-gis.vercel.app
   ```
   Then re-fetch and confirm.
6. Report the verified live URL only after step 4/5 succeeds.

Known pitfall: Git push can update a deployment whose production alias is `martin-guthrie-gis-rust.vercel.app` while the primary domain stays stuck on an older deployment. Always verify the primary domain, not just "Ready" status. Prefer `npx vercel --prod` then explicitly alias the returned Production URL when needed.

Do not leave local-only changes undeployed after a completed task.
If git ownership/safe.directory blocks commands, use `git -c safe.directory=<repo-path> ...` per command — do not change global git config.
